# Searching Files

## find

Search files and directories recursively.

| Command                        | Description                              |
| ------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| `find .`                       | Search everything from current directory |
| `find ~`                       | Search from home directory               |
| `find . -name "file"`          | Search by exact filename                 |
| `find . -name "*.txt"`         | Search by extension                      |
| `find . -iname "*.txt"`        | Case-insensitive search                  |
| `find . -type f`               | Find regular files                       |
| `find . -type d`               | Find directories                         |
| `find . -empty`                | Find empty files/directories             |
| `find . -size +10M`            | Files larger than 10 MB                  |
| `find . -size -1M`             | Files smaller than 1 MB                  |
| `find . -mtime -1`             | Modified within the last day             |
| `find . -mtime +30`            | Modified more than 30 days ago           |
| `find . -name "*.tmp" -delete` | Delete matching files                    |

> **Tip:** Always quote wildcard patterns when using `find`.

Example:

```bash
find . -name "*.log"
```

---

## locate

Search using a prebuilt database.

```bash
locate README.md
```

Update the database:

```bash
sudo updatedb
```

Install if needed:

```bash
sudo apt install locate
```

---

## which

Show the executable path of a command.

```bash
which git
which bash
which python3
```

---

## whereis

Show executable, source files, and manual pages.

```bash
whereis bash
whereis git
```

